[[File:John Szwed at Kelly Writers House.jpg|right|thumb|John Szwed at the [[Kelly Writers House]] in 2015]] '''John F. Szwed''' (born 1936) is the John M. Musser Professor Emeritus of Anthropology, African American Studies and Film Studies at [[Yale University]] and an Adjunct Senior Research Scholar in the Center for Jazz Studies at [[Columbia University]], where he previously served as the Center's Director and Professor of Music and Jazz Studies. Szwed is the author of many books on jazz and American music, including studies of [[Sun Ra]], [[Miles Davis]], [[Jelly Roll Morton]], [[Alan Lomax]] and [[Billie Holiday]].
==Career== Szwed received a B.S. in business and economics from [[Marietta College]] in 1958. He also studied trombone and music theory and played professionally for twelve years; as an undergraduate, he worked in a steel mill and performed at roadhouses, country clubs, college dances and speakeasies in Ohio and [[West Virginia]]. Thereafter, he enrolled at [[Ohio State University]], where he earned a second bachelor's degree in communications in 1959, an [[M.A.]] in communications in 1960 and a [[Ph.D.]] in [[sociology]] and [[anthropology]] in 1965. His graduate school adviser was anthropology pioneer [[Erika Bourguignon]], who encouraged him to bring to his work what he already knew and experienced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d5p0BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&dq=%22john+szwed%22+%22ohio+state%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiywffFjtPNAhVMHT4KHQTXC-EQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=%22john+szwed%22+%22ohio+state%22&f=false|title=Crossovers: Essays on Race, Music, and American Culture|first=John|last=Szwed|date=19 October 2006|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|accessdate=6 November 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.college.columbia.edu/sites/default/files/2013-2014_columbia_college_bulletin.pdf|format=PDF|title=Columbia College : BULLETIN : 2013–2014|website=College.columbia.edu|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> His work as an anthropologist and folklorist includes field studies in Newfoundland, the [[Georgia Sea Islands]], and [[Trinidad]].<ref name = "Lomax">{{cite web| url = https://www.loc.gov/folklife/lomax/lomaxbios.html| title = Participant Biographies, The American Folklife Center| accessdate = August 19, 2011| publisher = The Library of Congress}}</ref>
From 1982 to 2008, Szwed was John M. Musser Professor of Anthropology, African American Studies and Film Studies at [[Yale University]].<ref name="centerforjazz">{{cite web| url = http://www.jazz.columbia.edu/index.html| title = The center for jazz studies at Columbia University| accessdate = 19 August 2011| website = Jazz.columbia.edu| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110917212831/http://www.jazz.columbia.edu/index.html| archivedate = 17 September 2011| df = }}</ref> Szwed was appointed term Professor of Music and Jazz Studies at Columbia University in 2008, a position he held through 2014. From 2011 to 2014, he was Director of the Center for Jazz Studies at Columbia.<ref name = "centerforjazz"/> He has also taught at [[New York University]] and the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he was Director of the Center for Urban Ethnography and Chair of the Department of Folklore.<ref name = "Lomax"/> Szwed is married to Marilyn Anderson Szwed and lives in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].
==Publications== In 2000, Szwed published a study of [[Sun Ra]], ''Space is the Place: The Lives and Times of Sun Ra''.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=53| title = Space is the Place: The Life and Times of Sun Ra| author = Wuethrich, Matthew| date = January 24, 2003| accessdate = August 19, 2011|website=Allaboutjazz.com}}</ref> In 2003, he published a [[Miles Davis]] biography, ''So What: The Life of Miles Davis''.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://yalereviewofbooks.com/so-what-the-life-of-miles-davis-book-by-john-szwed-reviewed-by-tom-isler/| title = So What: The Life of Miles Davis book by John Szwed reviewed by Tom Isler| author = Isler, Tom| accessdate = October 5, 2015| website=Yalereviewofbooks.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/so-what-the-life-of-miles-davis-by-john-szwed-605639.html| title = So what: the life of Miles Davis | author = Morton, Brian| date = November 30, 2002| accessdate = August 19, 2011| website=Independent.co.uk}}</ref> Szwed wrote ''Doctor Jazz'', a booklet about Jelly Roll Morton for the 2005 issue of ''[[Jelly Roll Morton the Complete Library of Congress Recording|The Complete Library of Congress Recordings by Alan Lomax]]'' on [[Rounder Records]]. The booklet won the 2005 [[Grammy Award for Best Album Notes]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&title=&year=2005&genre=21| title = Best Album Notes, 2005| accessdate = August 19, 2011| website=Grammy.com}}</ref> In 2010, Szwed published a biography of [[Alan Lomax]], the [[folklore|folklorist]], [[ethnomusicology|ethnomusicologist]], and [[Field work|field collector]] of [[folk music]] of the 20th century, entitled ''The Man Who Recorded the World''.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/16/entertainment/la-ca-john-szwed-20110116| title = Alan Lomax: The Man Who Recorded the World| author = Smith, Wendy| date = January 16, 2011| accessdate = August 19, 2011| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/31/books/31book.html| title = Singing the Perfectionist-Folkie Blues| author = Maslin, Janet| date = January 30, 2011| accessdate = August 19, 2011|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>
In 2015, Szwed published ''Billie Holiday: The Musician and the Myth'', which analyses the art of [[Billie Holiday|Billie Holiday's]] singing and the construction of her life as a mythic paradigm of African American suffering. Szwed argues that Holiday's autobiography, ''[[Lady Sings the Blues (book)|Lady Sings the Blues]]'', is a generally accurate account of Holiday's life, and that Holiday's co-writer, [[William Dufty]], was forced to water down or suppress material by the threat of legal action. ''[[The New Yorker]]'' reviewer [[Richard Brody]] writes: "In particular, Szwed traces the stories of two important relationships that are missing from the book—with [[Charles Laughton]], in the nineteen-thirties, and with [[Tallulah Bankhead]], in the late nineteen-forties—and of one relationship that’s sharply diminished in the book, her affair with [[Orson Welles]] around the time of ''[[Citizen Kane]]''."<ref name=NY>{{cite news|author=Brody, Richard|title=The Art of Billie Holiday's Life |url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-art-of-billie-holidays-life |accessdate=April 6, 2015|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|date=April 3, 2015}}</ref>
