{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} '''The Moving Museum''' is a not-for-profit organisation that runs a nomadic programme of [[contemporary art]] exhibitions. It has held projects in [[Dubai]],<ref>[http://www.arabnews.com/news/445535 Dubai Hosts 'Moving Museum' in Its Backyard.] ''Arab News'', 21 March 2013. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref><ref>Shabi, Rachel. [http://gu.com/p/3txpf/sbl Could Palates, Rather than Politics, Be the Key to Peace in the Middle East?] ''The Guardian''. 13 August 2013. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref> [[Istanbul]],<ref>Baumgardner, Julie. [http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/06/istanbul-moving-museum-ark-kultur-jumana-manna/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 A Nomadic Museum Takes Up Temporary Residence in Istanbul.] ''The New York Times Blog'', 6 August 2014. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref> and [[London]]<ref>Harris, Gareth. [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/090a766c-2ce9-11e3-8281-00144feab7de.html#axzz2idChQrc4 The Duo behind the Moving Museum]. ''Financial Times''. 11 October 2013. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref><ref>Pilger, Zoe. [http://ind.pn/1Hajg37 Art Review: Open Heart Surgery, The Moving Museum, London.] ''The Independent''. 30 October 2013. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref> comprising large-scale exhibitions, [[Artist-in-residence|artist residencies]],<ref>Senova, Basak. [http://www.flashartonline.com/2015/02/on-artist-in-residency-platform-the-moving-museum-istanbul/ On Artist-in-residency Platform THE MOVING MUSEUM / Istanbul.] ''Flash Art International''. 4 February 2015. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref> public programming, publishing, [[Commission (art)|artwork commissions]], and digital programming.<ref>Ellwood, Mark. [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-05/meet-the-art-museum-that-will-follow-you-around-the-internet Meet the Art Museum That Will Follow You Around the Internet.] ''Bloomberg.com''. Bloomberg, 5 May 2015. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref>
Artists are invited through a collaborative curatorial model composed of contributors from various disciplines and are included in diverse ways: as producers, collaborators, curators, and advisors. Over 50 new projects have been commissioned across a wide range of media<ref>Over 50 works commissioned across sites in Istanbul [http://www.thevinylfactory.com/vinyl-factory-exhibitions/photo-gallery-the-vinyl-factory-touch-down-in-istanbul-for-the-launch-of-nomadic-exhibition-the-moving-museum/ ('commissions by 40 artists')] and London [http://babylondonorbital.blogspot.co.uk/2013/11/the-moving-museum-open-heart-surgery.html ('produced 31 separate solo presentations')] and online [http://www.theguideistanbul.com/news/view/1775/the-moving-museum-in-istanbul/ ('appointed four of the world’s most important internet artists')]</ref> including works by [[Amalia Ulman]], [[Broomberg and Chanarin]], Clunie Reid, Hannah Perry, [[Hito Steyerl]], [[Jeremy Deller]], [[Jon Rafman]], Jeremy Bailey, [[James Bridle]], [[Michael Rakowitz]], [[Tom Sachs (artist)|Tom Sachs]], [[Ryan Gander]], [[Mai-Thu Perret]], [[Slavs and Tatars]], [[Zach Blas]], Anne de Vries, Ben Schumacher, Ming Wong and Lucky PDF.
The Moving Museum is an independent and non-political organization founded by Aya Mousawi and Simon Sakhai in 2012; a registered [[Community Interest Company]] (CIC) in England and Wales;<ref>[http://artreview.com/news/news_10_jun_2014_moving_museum_istanbul_residency_and_exhibition/ Peripatetic Contemporary Art Organisation The Moving Museum Launch Residency and Group Exhibition in Istanbul.] ''ArtReview''. 10 June 2014. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref> and a registered 501(c)(3) Charity in the United States of America. The organisation's [http://www.themovingmuseum.com/ website] was designed by new media artist [http://jeremybailey.net/ Jeremy Bailey] with Harm van den Dorpel, Joe Hamilton, and Jonas Lund.<ref>Westall, Mark. [http://fadmagazine.com/2015/02/10/themovingmuseum-launches-online/ @TheMovingMuseum Launches Online.] ''FAD Magazine''. 10 February 2015. Retrieved 6 July 2015.</ref>
